summaries.title: Summary 307.1
summaries.summaryText: Daniel expressed pride in representing his family’s aspirations but also noted ongoing struggles with imposter syndrome. He values belonging through peer groups that normalize his experiences as a first-gen student of color in STEM. [Part 4/4]

summaries.title: Summary 307.2
summaries.summaryText: Ethan discussed observing classmates who struggled to access tutoring or networking opportunities. His reflection on his own privilege as a continuing-generation student led him to advocate for more peer tutoring support and accessible design lab hours. [Part 3/4]

summaries.title: Summary 307.3
summaries.summaryText: Priya balanced heavy research commitments with cultural obligations, feeling pressure to excel as a first-gen Indian-American student in tech. [Part 2/4]

timelinePoints.eventDescription: Joined the Society of Hispanic Professional Engineers during her first semester to find community and mentorship. [Timeline 1]
Became lead designer on the robotics team, guiding a diverse group of underclassmen through competition preparation. [Timeline 3]
Struggled during his first programming course, leading him to seek help from tutoring and peers. [Timeline 4]
Served as a teaching assistant for an introductory design course, emphasizing peer inclusivity. [Timeline 4]

themes.title: Family Expectations and Cultural Motivation
themes.description: Cultural values around family honor and sacrifice serve both as motivation and a source of pressure for first-generation Vietnamese-American students pursuing STEM. [Extended 1]

themes.title: Acknowledging Structural Advantage and Allyship in STEM
themes.description: Ethan’s reflections underscore the role of allyship among students who recognize their positional privilege. He highlights how acknowledging systemic inequities can lead to more equitable classroom dynamics. [Extended 3]

themes.title: Normalizing Mental Health Conversations in STEM
themes.description: Sarah’s work highlights the growing student-led shift toward wellness advocacy within rigorous majors. [Extended 1]

quotes.quoteText: My parents don’t really understand what I study, but they tell everyone I’m going to be an engineer — that means a lot, but it’s also scary. [Context 2]
I love leading projects, but it’s exhausting always being the one to explain why diversity matters in engineering teams. [Context 4]
My parents say, ‘Just do your best,’ but I can tell they really mean, ‘Don’t waste this chance we gave you.’ [Context 1]
My parents always say 'you represent the family'—it motivates me but also adds pressure. [Context 4]

areasForImprovement.title: Expand Peer Mentoring for First-Generation STEM Students
areasForImprovement.description: Formalize mentoring programs that pair upperclassmen with first-generation students early in their academic journey. These networks reduce imposter syndrome and improve retention rates. [Extended 1]

areasForImprovement.title: Formal Recognition for Student Advocacy and Mentorship Work
areasForImprovement.description: Students like Aaliyah contribute substantial unpaid labor in mentoring and advocacy roles. Institutions should recognize these contributions as part of leadership and service learning frameworks. [Extended 3]

areasForImprovement.title: Increase Mentorship for Women in Computing
areasForImprovement.description: Expand mentorship and career guidance for women and first-gen students. [Extended 3]

areasForImprovement.title: Integrate Wellness Programming into STEM Curriculum
areasForImprovement.description: Develop optional workshops or credit modules linking mental health and STEM performance. [Extended 4]
